"Chapter 5 built a flock and touched three tunings — birds, fish,
nervous crowd. This appendix is the tuning table. Twelve rows, each
a distinct flock character. Copy the preset, run it, tune from
there.

The three tuning knobs are:

- `align-r`     : radius within which we match neighbors' direction
- `cohere-r`    : radius within which we move toward neighbor centroid
- `separate-r`  : radius within which we STRONGLY steer away
- `separate-force` : strength of the separation kick (higher = more nervous)

There's a fourth implicit knob (max-force), which we hold constant
here at 0.06. Raising it makes the flock more responsive; lowering
it makes it lazier and blobbier.

---

## C.1 The tuning table

| # | Name                 | align-r | cohere-r | sep-r | sep-force | Character                                                            |
|---|----------------------|--------:|---------:|------:|----------:|----------------------------------------------------------------------|
| 1 | Starling             |   80    |    60    |  15   |    1.5    | Fast unified formation, occasional split-and-rejoin                  |
| 2 | Sardines             |   60    |   100    |  18   |    2.0    | Dense elongated school, smooth turns                                 |
| 3 | Sparrows in bush     |   30    |    40    |  25   |    3.0    | Cluster of dispersed individuals, all facing similar directions      |
| 4 | Bees swarm           |   20    |    50    |  10   |    1.2    | Ball-like swarm; individuals wobble inside a cohesive envelope       |
| 5 | Nervous crowd        |   40    |    60    |  30   |    4.0    | Restless, avoids close contact, no clear formation                   |
| 6 | Flowing river of fish|   90    |    80    |  12   |    1.8    | Long streaming line that curves like a river                         |
| 7 | Bomber squadron      |   120   |    40    |  25   |    2.5    | Wide-formation flying with spacing                                   |
| 8 | Confused flock       |   20    |    30    |  15   |    1.0    | Small clusters that don't merge; fragmented behavior                 |
| 9 | Whirlpool            |   60    |    90    |  10   |    1.5    | Boids form a rotating vortex around their center                     |
|10 | Dispersed grazers    |   10    |    20    |  40   |    2.5    | Individuals spread across the field, minimal coordination            |
|11 | Wave pattern         |  100    |    60    |  15   |    1.5    | Flock forms visible longitudinal waves as it moves                   |
|12 | Migration V          |   85    |    50    |  20   |    2.0    | Long-range coherent formation, individuals in visible ranks          |

## C.2 Preset code

```scheme
(define flocking-presets
  '((starling            (align . 80)  (cohere . 60)  (separate . 15) (sf . 1.5))
    (sardines            (align . 60)  (cohere . 100) (separate . 18) (sf . 2.0))
    (sparrows-in-bush    (align . 30)  (cohere . 40)  (separate . 25) (sf . 3.0))
    (bees-swarm          (align . 20)  (cohere . 50)  (separate . 10) (sf . 1.2))
    (nervous-crowd       (align . 40)  (cohere . 60)  (separate . 30) (sf . 4.0))
    (flowing-river       (align . 90)  (cohere . 80)  (separate . 12) (sf . 1.8))
    (bomber-squadron     (align . 120) (cohere . 40)  (separate . 25) (sf . 2.5))
    (confused-flock      (align . 20)  (cohere . 30)  (separate . 15) (sf . 1.0))
    (whirlpool           (align . 60)  (cohere . 90)  (separate . 10) (sf . 1.5))
    (dispersed-grazers   (align . 10)  (cohere . 20)  (separate . 40) (sf . 2.5))
    (wave-pattern        (align . 100) (cohere . 60)  (separate . 15) (sf . 1.5))
    (migration-v         (align . 85)  (cohere . 50)  (separate . 20) (sf . 2.0))))

(define (apply-preset preset-name n)
  (let* ((preset (cdr (assoc preset-name flocking-presets))))
    (flock-character n
      (cdr (assoc 'align preset))
      (cdr (assoc 'cohere preset))
      (cdr (assoc 'separate preset))
      (cdr (assoc 'sf preset)))))

(apply-preset 'starling 80)
```

## C.3 How to READ the parameter space

The three radii and one force form a 4D space. Some regions are dead
(no flock forms). Some are single-formation. Some are multi-flock.

Rules of thumb:

- **cohere-r > align-r > separate-r**: birds. Formation is loose.
- **align-r == cohere-r**: fish schools. Everything the flock coheres
  to is also aligned with, so alignment reinforces cohesion.
- **cohere-r >> align-r**: agents attract from far and only align
  when close. Result: a blob that migrates.
- **separate-r > cohere-r**: individuals push apart faster than they
  attract. Result: dispersed grazing, no flock.
- **align-r >> everything**: agents pick up flock direction from very
  far away. Result: long-range coherence, waves, migration formations.
- **separate-force > 3 * ambient forces**: nervous behavior.

## C.4 Character-first design

Instead of tweaking numbers to see what happens, START with the
character you want, then look up its region:

- Want tightly-packed schooling? Sardines preset.
- Want dispersed but oriented (like sparrows on a lawn)? Sparrows in
  bush.
- Want a defensive ball (like a fish bait-ball)? Bees swarm with
  higher separation.
- Want migration in a visible V? Migration V.
- Want confused, cannot-form? Confused-flock.

## C.5 The obstacles knob

Add walls or a repellor (a phantom high-repulsion entity):

```scheme
;; A repellor at (240, 180) with radius 100 that pushes boids away.
(define repellor
  (let ((r (world/spawn 'repellor 240 180)))
    (entity/pin! r)
    (ai/separate r 'boid 100 6.0)
    r))
```

Watch: the flock avoids the repellor. If your flock's separation-
force is comparable to the repellor's, it will curl around the
repellor smoothly. If much less, boids might penetrate the
repulsion zone.

## C.6 The predator knob

Add a hawk that pursues the nearest boid; boids flee it.

```scheme
(let ((hawk (world/spawn 'hawk 240 40)))
  (entity/mass! hawk 1.0)
  (entity/max-speed! hawk 3.0)
  (ai/max-force! hawk 0.10)
  (ai/pursue hawk (world/nearest 'boid 240 40))
  (world/each 'boid (lambda (b) (ai/flee b hawk 100))))
```

The flock splits and reforms. Try starling preset + hawk; the split-
and-reform is dramatic. Try dispersed-grazers + hawk; the grazers
mostly ignore the hawk unless it's very close.

## C.7 The flow-field knob

A background wind that curls in a pattern.

```scheme
(ai/flow-field
  (lambda (x y)
    (vec/make (* 0.5 (cos (* 0.01 y)))
              (* 0.5 (sin (* 0.01 x))))))
(world/each 'boid (lambda (b) (ai/follow-flow b 0.4)))
```

The flow-field weight (0.4 in this example) is a fifth knob. Lower =
weaker background; higher = flow dominates over local flocking.

## C.8 The takeaway

The knobs are simple. The space is rich. Print this table, tape it
above your monitor, and reach for a preset when you know what
character you want. Iterate from there.

